    (380, 0, 'Privacy', 'Objection, this interrogatory improperly invades privacy rights protected by art I, § 1 of the California Constitution and the First Amendment to U.S. Constitution. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), § 18.35.', 'Objection, this interrogatory improperly invades privacy rights protected by art I, § 1 of the California Constitution and the First Amendment to U.S. Constitution. Cal. Judges Benchbook Civ. Proc. Discovery (August 2019), § 18.35.\r\n\r\n<b>Use Notes</b>\r\nSome courts used to require the party seeking private information to justify the need for it. Recently, however, the California Supreme Court reversed the burden. Now, &quot;the party asserting a privacy right must establish a legally protected privacy interest, an objectively reasonable expectation of privacy in the given circumstances, and a threatened intrusion that is serious.&quot; <i>Williams v. Superior Court</i> (2017) 3 Cal.5th 531, 552.', 1,1,1,0,0),
